        &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The virtual lack of data between \(50\) and \(60\) indicates a gap and suggest that we are in fact dealing with two separate features. The usual summary statistics that you might be tempted to calculate like mean, standard deviation, median and IQR are
    not of much use since neither set indicates the gap or skewness. Without visual representation, such as a histogram, a single-peaked distribution tends to be assumed which is not true in this case.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Final comments on data representations&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;You should not rely on summary statistics such as the mean and standard deviation or median and IQR alone to represent a data set. Remember that if a distribution has outliers, gaps, skewness or multiple peaks, then the shape is probably more important
        than location and spread.&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;The shape of a distribution is better shown visually than numerically. Remember that a histogram and box-and-whisker plots emphasises the detail contained in the tails of a distribution.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
